                  </objectDesc>
                  <handDesc>
                     <handNote scope="major" script="nastaliq" medium="ink">Written primarily in a
                        clear naskh hand tending towards nasta‘līq in <material>black</material>,
                        with subheaders in <material>red</material>, by <persName type="standard"
                           role="scr">Ḥusayn ibn Hasan</persName>.</handNote>
                     <handNote scope="minor" script="nastaliq" medium="ink">missing portions and
                        infilles written primarily in a hasty nasta‘līq script shikastah ligatures
                        in <material>black</material>, apparently by the same hand that completed
                           <ref target="https://www.fihrist.org.uk/catalog/manuscript_6656"
                              ><idno>Persian MS 173</idno></ref>.</handNote>
                  </handDesc>
                  <bindingDesc>
                     <binding notBefore="1808" notAfter="1818">
                        <p>Probably bound in the <placeName ref="http://vocab.getty.edu/page/tgn/7000208" key="place_7000208">Indian subcontinent</placeName> cert="high"
                              ref="http://vocab.getty.edu/page/tgn/7000208">India</country> in a
                           European-style full light brown goatskin <material>leather</material>
                           over <material>pasteboards</material>, with seven bands (four false) on
                           the spine, and squares along the edges, in a completely different manner
                           than other volumes in the set. Marbled endpapers and flyleaves
                           watermarked with a large crest and countermarked with the name of
                                 <watermark><persName role="ppm">George
                              Smidts</persName></watermark>. Decorative single-core endbands at head
                           and tail sewn in yellow and green <material>silk</material>. Paper label
                           on the spine bears the title of the volume in Persian.</p>
                        <p><dimensions type="binding" unit="mm">
                              <height>324</height>
                              <width>222</width>
                              <depth>42</depth>
                           </dimensions>
                        </p>
                        <condition>Handle with caution. In fair condition, with with the exterior
                           binding joints breaking and significant abrasion to the surface, and
                           dry-rot. Boxed.</condition>
                     </binding>
                  </bindingDesc>
               </physDesc>
               <history>
                  <origin><origPlace>Completed in Dhoraji, then part of <settlement type="state"
                           ref="http://viaf.org/viaf/124458986">Gondal State</settlement> one of
                        eight princely states then within the <settlement type="province"
                           ref="http://viaf.org/viaf/127804822">Bombay Presidency</settlement> in
                           the <placeName ref="http://vocab.getty.edu/page/tgn/7000208" key="place_7000208">Indian subcontinent</placeName> cert="high" ref="http://vocab.getty.edu/page/tgn/7000208"
                        >India</country></origPlace> completed on <origDate calendar="#Hijri_qamari"
                        when="1808-12-22">4 Ẕī-al-Qa‘dah, 1223 AH (22 Dec. 1808 CE)</origDate> by
                     <persName role="scr" key="person_f6589">Muḥammad ‘Alī ibn Muḥammad
                     Shafī‘</persName></origin>
                  <provenance><p> Likely completed for, or obtained by <persName type="standard"
                           role="fmo" ref="http://viaf.org/viaf/19247044" key="person_19247044"
                           >Jonathan Duncan</persName>, who governed the <settlement type="province"
                           ref="http://viaf.org/viaf/127804822">Bombay Presidency</settlement> for
                        sixteen years.</p></provenance>
                  <provenance><p>After Duncan's death, his family sold his library through the <placeName ref="http://vocab.getty.edu/page/tgn/7011781">London</placeName> 
                     firm of <persName role="auc" ref=" http://viaf.org/viaf/10201461" key="person_10201461">Samuel Leigh Sotheby (1805–1861)</persName> 
                     where <persName role="fmo ins" ref="http://viaf.org/viaf/32750828" key="person_32750828">Sir Graves Champney Haughton (1788–1849)</persName>, 
                     an early student at Fort William College who excelled in the study of several oriental languages, 
                     purchased it as per his inscription on folio <locus from="1b" to="1b"
                           >1b</locus> dated <date calendar="#Gregorian" when="1818-02">Feb.
                           1818</date>. </p></provenance>
                  <provenance><p>Later owned by Persian scholar <persName type="standard" role="fmo"
                           ref="http://viaf.org/viaf/20108923/" key="person_20108923">Nathaniel
                           Bland (1803–1865)</persName>, after whose death <placeName ref="http://vocab.getty.edu/page/tgn/7011781" key="place_7011781">London</placeName> antiquarian
                        dealer <persName type="standard" role="bsl"
                           ref="http://viaf.org/viaf/5679225/" key="person_5679225">Bernard Quaritch
                           (1819–1899)</persName> sold his oriental manuscripts to <persName
                           type="standard" role="fmo" ref="http://viaf.org/viaf/97751058/"
                           key="person_97751058">Alexander Lindsay, 25th Earl of Crawford
                           (1812–1880)</persName> in <date calendar="#Gregorian" when="1866"
                           >1866</date>.</p>
                  </provenance>
                  <provenance>
                     <p>Purchased by <persName type="standard" role="dnr" key="person_f6379"
                           >Enriqueta Rylands (1843–1908)</persName> in <date calendar="#Gregorian"
                           when="1901">1901</date> from <persName type="standard" role="fmo"
                           ref="http://viaf.org/viaf/9985420/" key="person_9985420">James Ludovic
                           Lindsay, 26th Earl of Crawford (1847–1913)</persName>.</p>
                  </provenance>
                  <acquisition>
                     <p>Bequeathed by <persName type="standard" role="dnr" key="person_f6379"
                           >Enriqueta Rylands (1843–1908)</persName> in <date calendar="#Gregorian"
                           when="1908">1908</date> to the <orgName type="corporation" role="rps"
                           ref="http://viaf.org/viaf/312795145/">John Rylands
                        Library</orgName>.</p>
                  </acquisition>
               </history>
